Name: Argentina Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1884 To Dec 1992
Quarterly From Mar 1993 To Jun 2019
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated, both in millions of pesos and as a percentage rate of change, on GDP at current and constant 1993 prices. The data cover the entire economy.  Data on gross national income are disseminated in millions of pesos at nominal (Q) and constant (annual) 1993 price values. Data on savings are disseminated in millions of pesos at nominal (Q) and constant 1993 price values.  The gross domestic saving is presented quarterly as national saving and external saving (Q); and annually as public, private and external saving. The data are compiled using the production method. Data are disseminated showing a breakdown by production sector at the one digit level of ISIC Revision 3 classification.  The data are compiled in accordance with the methodology set out in the SNA 93. The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Mexico Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1895 To Dec 1980
Quarterly From Mar 1981 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Source: GDP (million current LCU): Figures for 1900-1987 are from INEGI (1990), no data for Mexico during the Revolution (1911-1920). Figures for 1988-2000 are from IMF IFS (2002b). Break in continuity 1987/8. Figures are expressed in Gold Pesos (GP) from 1900-1931, Silver Pesos (SP) from 1932-1992, and New Pesos (NP) from 1993-2000 using the 2008 Base numbers.Notes: Data are disseminated in millions of Mexican pesos and at annual rates on GDP at current prices and constant 1993 prices, by sector of activity (NACE (rev.1) and by expenditure method. Data are disseminated showing a breakdown by private consumption, government consumption, gross capital formation by public and private sectors, changes in stocks, exports of goods and services, and imports of goods and services. Total GDP at constant prices and seasonally adjusted is also shown. Corresponding implicit deflators are included. Data are prepared according to the United Nations 1993 "System of National Accounts". Not included are unlawful activities such as the manufacturing and distribution of narcotic drugs, contraband and illegal transportation of merchandise, and activities (medicine, for example) practiced by persons not entitled to exercise a profession.

Name: South Africa Annualized Gross Domestic Product
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1911 To Dec 1959
Quarterly From Mar 1960 To Mar 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated in millions of rand on value added by industry and gross domestic product (GDP) at nominal and constant 2000 price values, compiled according to the production method. The breakdown by kind of economic activity is disseminated for both the current and constant 2000 prices for the following: (1) Agriculture, forestry and fishing; (2) Mining and quarrying; (3) Manufacturing; (4) Electricity, gas and water; (5) Construction (contractors); (6) Wholesale and retail trade, catering and accommodation; (7) Transport, storage and communication; (8) Finance, insurance, real estate and business services; (9) Personal services; and (10) General government services.   The data are compiled according to the 1993 SNA and are published in both original and seasonally adjusted forms, as well as in annualized rates. See also the separate DSBB page on GDP compiled by the expenditure method.

Name: United States Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1789 To Dec 1920
Quarterly From Mar 1921 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Sources: Annual data before 1929 are taken from Historical Statistics of the United States, Colonial times to 1970, Washington: U.S. Dept. of Commerce, and B.R. Mitchell, International Historical Statistics: The Americas 1750-1992, Fourth Edition, New York: Stockton Press, 1998; Bureau of the Census, U.S. Govt. Print. Off., 1975; Quarterly data are from the US Bureau of Economic Analysis which calculates the GDP data. Notes: Data are in billions of US Dollars. Data are disseminated in current prices and in real terms, with corresponding price indexes, for GDP and GNP by expenditure category; in current prices for national income, personal income and saving; and, in real terms for disposable personal income and per capita disposable income. Detailed data on GDP are published for the following expenditure categories: personal consumption expenditure; private fixed investment in structures;private fixed investment in equipment and software; change in private inventories; exports; imports; Federal government consumption expenditures and gross investment; state and local government consumption expenditure and gross investment. Detailed components of national income, personal income, and consumption of fixed capital are also published. Current price estimates are generally presented in billions of dollars; real measures are presented in both index form and in dollars and are calculated using the chained Fisher index formula (reference year, 1996). Quarterly estimates are seasonally adjusted and at annual rates. The geographic coverage of the data is the 50 States and the District of Columbia. All legal activities are covered (certain non-market activities by imputation). Activities reflect the entire period (year or quarter). GDP is recorded on a production timing basis; consistent with production, national income and its components are largely on an accrual basis; personal taxes are on a cash basis and personal income is largely on a cash basis. The personal sector covers households and nonprofit institutions serving individuals; the business sector covers, in addition to businesses organized for profit, mutual financial institutions, private noninsured pension funds, cooperatives, government enterprises, and nonprofit institutions that primarily serve business. Basic data include economic censuses taken at 5-year intervals; annual, quarterly, and monthly statistical surveys; decennial censuses of housing and residential finance; budgetary and administrative information, including tabulations of tax returns; and private trade sources. The United States has either already adopted, or is moving towards adopting, the most important changes included in the 1993 SNA.Source: Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis. The data is collected from the FRED database. The FRED database uses data from the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System, the Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia, the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, The White House Council of Economic Advisors and Office of Management and Budget, the Congressional Budget Office, the U.S. Department of Commerce, the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development, the Bureau of Labor Statistics and the U.S. Department of the Treasury. The GDP methodology was revised in 2013.  This increased the 1929 values by about 1%.  To reflect this, all data prior to 1929 were increased by 1% for consistency.

Name: Australia Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Jun 1788 To Jun 1959
Quarterly From Sep 1959 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Historical annual data are taken from Russell, International Historical Statistics and http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/Previousproducts/1301.0Feature%20Article502001?opendocument&tabname=Summary&prodno=1301.0&issue=2001&num=&view.  There was a change of methodology in 1959 producing a large change in nominal GDP.Notes: Data are disseminated in millions of Australian dollars for both current price data and chained volume measures of GDP. The current price estimates of GDP are compiled using both the income and the expenditure approaches, whereas the chain volume estimates of GDP are compiled using both the production and the expenditure approaches.  The chain volume measures are obtained by applying annually-reweighted chain Laspeyres volume changes to the current price values of a chosen reference year, which is always the last but one full financial year ending June 30 for which the data are available. The so-called "headline" chain volume measure is referred to simply as GDP and is the average of the three independent measures. The "headline" measure of GDP at current prices is obtained by reflating the chain volume measure of GDP using the expenditure implicit price deflator. The following breakdowns of GDP are disseminated: (1) By expenditure category, which includes household consumption, government consumption, gross fixed capital formation by government and by enterprises, changes in inventories, and exports and imports of goods and services.(2) By productive sectors. Using the Australian and New Zealand Standard Industrial Classification (ANZSIC), information is provided by division for all industries. Additional breakdowns are provided for the agriculture, forestry and fishing; mining; manufacturing; electricity, gas and water; and transport and storage industries.(3) By income components, which include compensation of employees, gross operating surplus, gross mixed income and taxes less subsidies on production and imports.A wide range of data sources are used in the compilation of the quarterly national accounts. Virtually every economic collection (censuses and surveys) undertaken by the ABS is used, along with a range of administrative by-product statistics (including taxation statistics, motor vehicle registration data, customs data, etc.). Quarterly estimates are compiled from direct source data where possible. If direct source data are not available, the most suitable indicator series is used to allocate annual estimates to quarters and to extrapolate from the latest annual benchmark. Where no suitable quarterly indicator can be obtained, annual estimates are allocated to quarters and extrapolated using a mathematical trend formula. Seasonally adjusted estimates are provided for the current price gross domestic product and its income and expenditure components, national income account, national capital account, external account, general government income account, household income account estimates and for chain volume measures for GDP and its expenditure and industry components. Standard ABS seasonal adjustment methods are used except for various farm crops for which a special method is used. Australia's national accounts are compiled on the basis of the 1993 System of National Accounts. Transactions are recorded as far as possible on a change of ownership basis.Quarterly data on the "encouraged" components of saving and gross national income are available from the income account

Name: Hong Kong Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1913 To Dec 1972
Quarterly From Mar 1973 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
Source: Hong Kong Monetary Authority

Notes: Data are disseminated in millions of Hong Kong dollars on GDP in current and constant 2000 prices, together with implicit price deflators. The data cover the territory administered by the Government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and all economic sectors of the economy. Data on transactions with the mainland of China are treated as external transactions. The quarterly constant price GDP figures are compiled using both the expenditure and production approaches, whereas the quarterly current price figures are compiled by expenditure approach. Current price GDP by production approach is compiled annually. The GDP compiled by expenditure approach is adopted as the single measure of GDP. The following breakdowns of GDP are compiled and disseminated: (a) by expenditure component, which includes private consumption expenditure; government consumption expenditure; gross domestic fixed capital formation; changes in inventories; exports of goods; exports of services; imports of goods; and imports of services. (b) by economic activity, in which economic activities are classified according to the Hong Kong Standard Industrial Classification version 1.1 (HSIC V1.1), with two additional items, viz. ownership of premises and Financial Intermediation Services Indirectly Measured (FISIM). The concepts and definitions follow the 1993 "System of National Accounts" (SNA). Seasonally adjusted data are also published.

Name: India Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1870 To Dec 1995
Quarterly From Mar 1996 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
Original Source: S. Sivasubramonian, The National Income of India in the Twentieth Century, (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2000). The figures relate to Undivided India, comprising the territory of the future Indian Union, plus Pakistan and Bangladesh. Birma is excluded.
Definition: Data are in the process to be compiled according to SNA93. India presently uses a mix of the SNA68 and the SNA93. For the estimates of GDP by economic activity, India follows its National Industrial Classification 1987 (NIC-1987) which is broadly based on ISIC Rev.2. Coverage: The data cover the entire economy: all activities within SNA production boundary. However, production of goods (other than those in the agriculture, forestry and fishing) within the households for their own final consumption are not included. Collection: The data is mainly collected from respective administrative ministries or departments of Government of India. Calculation: Data are released one quarter after the end of the reference quarter. Annual data are the sum of quarterly figures. The data do not become final for approximately three years. Constant prices estimates are fixed base using 1993-1994 prices.

Name: Indonesia Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1921 To Dec 1989
Quarterly From Mar 1990 To Jun 2017
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated on quarterly GDP at current and constant 1993 market prices, in billions of Indonesian Rupiah, compiled by both the production approach and the expenditure approach. The data are reported at factor cost to 1963.  The GDP data cover the entire economy. The data compiled using the production approach are disseminated with a breakdown of total GDP by production sector as follows: agriculture; mining and quarrying; manufacturing industry; electricity, gas and clean water; construction; trade, hotels and restaurants; transportation and communication; finance, leasing and business services; and other services. The data compiled using the expenditure approach are disseminated with a breakdown of total GDP by expenditure category as follows: consumption expenditure by household; consumption expenditure by government; gross fixed capital formation; change in stock; exports of goods and services; and imports of goods and services. Data on GNP are also available after GDP is added to net factor income from abroad and data on national income as well after GNP is deducted by net indirect taxes and depreciation. The data are compiled in accordance with the "System of National Accounts 1968". The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Israel Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1950 To Dec 1979
Quarterly From Mar 1980 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated in millions of NIS (new Israeli sheqels) on GDP in current and constant 1995 prices. The data are compiled using the expenditure method, and cover the entire economy. A breakdown of GDP in both current and constant prices is disseminated as follows: private consumption expenditure; general government consumption expenditure; gross fixed capital formation; increase in stocks; exports and imports of goods and services. Current and constant price data on GDP for the whole economy and GDP for the business sector are also disseminated. The data are defined and classified according to the System of National Accounts (SNA 1993), except that the definition of the product at market prices differs from the SNA definition in the following ways: (1) the value of the product does not cover taxes on imports; and (2) the value of the product includes other revenue components received by the exporters. Data on GDP including net taxes on imports are also published to enable international comparisons.  The data are disseminated in both original and seasonally adjusted formats.

Name: Korea (Republic of) Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1911 To Dec 1959
Quarterly From Mar 1960 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Data from 1911 to 1938 are for all of Korea.  Data from 1953 forward are for South Korea.Notes: Data are disseminated in billions of Korean won on GDP estimates at current and 2000 constant prices, together with deflators. As the basic method of compilation, the production approach, the expenditure approach and the income approach are used. The data are compiled primarily by the production approach considering accuracy and availability of the source data.  The following breakdowns of the current and constant price GDP data are disseminated:  (1) A breakdown by kind of economic activity into: agriculture forestry and fishing; mining and quarrying; manufacturing; electricity, gas and water supply; construction; wholesale and retail trade, restaurants and hotels; transport, storage and communication; financial intermediation, real estate, rental and business activities; public administration and defense, compulsory social security; education; health and social work; other service activities; taxes less subsidies on products. (2) A breakdown by expenditure category into: final consumption expenditure; gross capital formation; exports and imports of goods and services; and statistical discrepancy. Data on savings at current prices are also disseminated. The national accounts data are compiled following the analytical framework, concepts, definitions, accounting conventions, and classifications of the System of National Accounts 1993.  The data are published in both original and seasonally-adjusted format.

Name: Malaysia Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1947 To Dec 1990
Quarterly From Mar 1991 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
Source: Bank Negara Malaysia

Notes: The data from 1947 to 1953 include both the federation of Malaya and Singapore. No data are available for 1954. Data from 1955 on are for Malaysia only.Data are disseminated in millions of Ringgit on GDP at current prices and constant 1987 prices, compiled by both the expenditure method and the production method. The data cover the entire country, and all activities, except illegal activities. Data are disseminated showing breakdowns of GDP as follows: (1) A breakdown by expenditure categories for both current and constant price GDP: government final consumption; private final consumption expenditure; changes in stocks; gross fixed capital formation; exports of goods and services; imports of goods and services; and GDP in purchasers' values. (2) A breakdown by production activity for both current and constant price GDP: agriculture, forestry and fishing; mining and quarrying; manufacturing; electricity, gas and water; construction; wholesale and retail trade, and restaurants and hotels; transport, storage and communication; finance, insurance, real estate and business services; other services; government services; less imputed bank service charges; plus: import duties; and GDP in purchasers' values. The data are compiled in accordance with the methodology set out in the SNA 1968. The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Peru Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1896 To Dec 1979
Quarterly From Mar 1980 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated in millions of nuevos soles on Gross Domestic Product (GDP) compiled by the expenditure method at current prices and at constant 1994 prices. GDP data compiled by the production method are available at constant 1994 prices only. The data cover the entire economy.  The economic activities considered for the estimates of quarterly national accounts are agriculture and livestock; fishing; mining and fuel (which is divided in metallic mining and fuel); manufacturing (which comprises primary and non-primary industries); electricity and water; construction; trade and other services. GDP by expenditure categories considers all the components of global demand and supply: private consumption, public consumption, private investment, public investment, changes in inventories, exports and imports of goods and non-financial services. Although the National Institute of Statistics and Informatics (INEI) has the responsability of preparing the national accounts, the Quarterly GDP data are prepared by the Central Reserve Bank of Peru (BCRP) using the expenditure method.  These estimates are consistent with the annual estimates published by the INEI and are derived from the monthly GDP results, calculated by the INEI using the production method. The classification of the data follows the 1993 edition of the UN System of National Accounts (SNA).  The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Philippines Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1946 To Dec 1980
Quarterly From Mar 1981 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: GDP and GNP estimates are disseminated at current levels and constant 1985 prices; in million of pesos, together with growth rates, implicit price deflators and percent distribution by industry and expenditure items. The estimates are presented in both the production and expenditure approach and cover the entire economy of the Philippines. GDP based on production is broken down by economic activity while factor incomes are estimated by institutional sector. GDP by expenditure share is disaggregated as follows: personal consumption; government consumption; fixed capital formation which includes construction, durable equipment and breeding stocks and orchard development; changes in stocks; export of goods (top 22 commodities) and services; and imports of goods (top 15 commodities) and services. GDP, GNP and Gross Value Added of Agriculture, Fishery and Forestry, Industry, Services and Personal Consumption Expenditure are seasonally adjusted on a quarterly basis.

Name: Russia Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1885 To Dec 1992
Quarterly From Mar 1993 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Definition: Data are compiled according to SNA 93. GDP is compiled using the production approach. The breakdown of GDP by expenditure categories includes statistical discrepancy that is determined as difference between produced and used GDP.  Collection: Data sources for production statistics include regular quarterly reports from enterprises, taxation records and agricultural sector reports. Reports are obtained from all large and medium sized enterprises, while data for small enterprises are estimated from quarterly sample surveys covering 20% of such units. Calculation: Data are released within 3 months after the end of the reference quarter. Quaterly data are revised seven months after the end of the reference quarter and in March of the second year following the reporting year (final data).

Periodicity:

Metadata: Source: Sugimoto, I., Economic growth of Singapore in the twentieth century, historical GDP estimates and empirical investigations, Economic Growth Centre Research Monograph Series, 2 (2011),

Name: Thailand Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1946 To Dec 1992
Quarterly From Mar 1993 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data on gross domestic product (GDP) and its components in production and expenditure are disseminated in million of Baht at current and constant 1988 prices. The data cover nationwide including formal and informal sectors, except illegal activities. Data on quarterly estimates showing the following breakdowns are disseminated:  (1) A breakdown of GDP at current prices and constant 1988 prices by production activity at the 1-digit level of ISIC, Rev. 3.  (2) A breakdown of GDP at current prices and constant 1988 prices by expenditure categories into: private consumption expenditure (PCE); gross fixed capital formation (GFCF); government consumption expenditure (GCE); change in inventories; exports; and imports. PCE, and GFCF are further broken down to the 1-digit level of the Central Product Classification (CPC). The constant prices data, except change in inventories and imports and exports are presented in both non-adjusted (original) and a seasonally adjusted formats. The current price data are published in the original format only.

Name: Turkey Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1870 To Dec 1986
Quarterly From Mar 1987 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data from before 1950 are from Gormez and Yigit (2015: series TR6B_A). Data are disseminated in millions of Turkish Liras (New Turkish Liras after 1/1/2005) on GDP in current and constant 1987 prices. The methodology changes in 1998 when a new base was introduced for 1998.  An adjustment is made between the two GDP series. The current and constant price data are compiled by both the expenditure method and the production method. The current price data are also compiled by the income method. The data cover the entire Turkish economy. Data showing a breakdown by major expenditure categories are disseminated in both current and constant prices as follows: private final consumption expenditure of consumer goods and services; government final consumption expenditure; gross fixed capital formation by public and private sector; change in inventories; and export and import of goods and services. The breakdown by productive sector using the ISIC Rev. 2 classification system shows estimates of valued added - in producers' prices - in both current and constant prices for: Agriculture, Livestock, Forestry and Fishing; Mining and Quarrying; Manufacturing; Electricity, Gas and Water Supply; Construction; Trade (including wholesale and retail), Hotel and Restaurant Services; Transport and Communications; Business and Personal Services; Ownership of Dwelling; and Government and Other Services. Nominal and Real Gross National Product (GNP) data in producers' prices are also disseminated. Income-based current price GDP data are disseminated showing a breakdown by taxes on production and imports; consumption of fixed capital; subsidies; compensation of employees (by kind of economic activity) and operating surplus. The data are compiled in accordance with the SNA 1968 methodology. The adoption of SNA 1993 and ESA95 is ongoing. The data are not seasonally adjusted. There are plans to seasonally adjust the data in the near future.

Quarterly From Mar 1987 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Source: Reserve Bank of New Zealand

Name: China Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1870 To Dec 1991
Quarterly From Mar 1992 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Definition: The National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) uses the 1993 SNA. The data sources used for China's national accounts include statistics collected by the National Bureau of Statistics and by other government ministries, financial statements and other administrative records.  Coverage: The data for Hong Kong and Macao Special Administrative Regions and Taiwan Province of China are not included in the national accounts of China. The national accounts cover all resident units including enterprises operating in special economic zones. In principal, all transactions covered in the 1993 SNA are included. Certain illegal activities are partly covered in the accounts, namely illegal imports (smuggling) and production and purchases of counterfeit goods.  Collection: Some of the statistics collected by the NBS and other government agencies are collected at the local level and pass through several aggregation stages before reaching the provincial administrations which send them to the NBS or government ministries responsible for collecting statistics in their areas of competence.

Name: Germany Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1850 To Dec 1959
Quarterly From Mar 1960 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Data from 1850 to 1938 are for all of Germany. Data from 1948 to 1959 exclude Saarland and West Berlin, data from 1960 to 1990 are for West Germany. Data from 1991 are for unified Germany. GDP excluding Saarland and West Berlin was 279 in 1960. Data for 1914 to 1924 and 1939 to 1949 are estimates based upon the real GDP data.
Notes: Data are disseminated on the quarterly results of origin, use and distribution calculation of the national accounts (VGR). The disseminated data for Germany include data on: current price GDP in billions of EUR; constant price GDP (1995=100) in billions of EUR; per-capita GDP; GNI; disposable income; and national income in EUR. Seasonally adjusted data for GDP, GNI, national income and utilization aggregates are also disseminated for Germany. The following breakdowns are disseminated: (1) Origination of the gross domestic product (BIP): nominal and real results according to six economic sectors (agriculture, forestry, and fishing; manufacturing, including energy; construction; trade and transport; financial, renting and business activities; and other service activities. (2) Use of the gross domestic product: nominal and real utilization aggregates and the pertinent price indices. (3) Distribution of national income: gross national income, net national income, income from employment and income from entrepreneurial activity and property, income originated domestically from employment and the gross wage and gross salary total according to six economic sectors and the net wage and salary total, disposable income and capital formation of all sectors and private households. The most important base statistics for the quarterly calculations are the production index, monthly construction reporting, monthly foreign trade statistics and other monthly and quarterly statistics.

Name: Greece Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1833 To Dec 1994
Quarterly From Mar 1995 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Data from 1830 to 1939 are from G. Kostelenos, "Historical Estimates of National Accounts Magnitudes in Greece, 1830-1939.",  Annual Data are from Russell, European Historical Statistics, and quarterly data are from Eurostat.

Name: Hungary Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1870 To Dec 1994
Quarterly From Mar 1995 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Pre-World War I data are from Jobst and Scheiber (2014: series AH6B_A). Data are disseminated in millions of forints (HUF) on GDP at current and constant 2000 prices compiled by the expenditure method. Production-based quarterly GDP are compiled using volume indices.The data cover the entire economy, except illegal activities such as drug dealing and prostitution. Adjustment made in 1957 to account for broadening of definition of NMP.  Data are disseminated showing a breakdown for the main expenditure categories as follows: household final consumption; government and NPISH's consumption; gross fixed capital formation (GFCF); changes in inventories; and exports and import of goods and services. GDP estimates, using the production approach, are broken down by industries (agriculture forestry and fishing; mining and quarrying; manufacturing and electricity; construction; and services - further broken down into 6 other service industries.) The data are compiled in accordance with the "System of National Accounts 1993" (SNA 1993) or ESA 1995. The data are seasonally adjusted for the first time in 2002.

Name: Iceland Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1901 To Jun 1988
Quarterly From Sep 1988 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated on GDP in current prices and constant prices (units of national currency) and as volume indices. The data cover the total economy, and are compiled using both the expenditure approach and the production approach. (The expenditure approach is the main method used in Iceland.)  A breakdown of the data is disseminated by industry, using a classification based on an Icelandic version of the former ISIC classification of 1958. From 1997 and onwards the NACE, rev. 1 activity classification has been implemented. A breakdown of the data by expenditure category is also published. (See Notes.) The data are compiled and classified according to the ESA 95.  Data on GNP and National Income, in current prices, constant prices and as volume indices, as well as data on Net Savings for the economy as a whole, are also disseminated. The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Ireland Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1861 To Dec 1996
Quarterly From Mar 1997 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Source for Pre-1920 data are Hills, Thomas, and Dimsdale (2015). GDP and GNP at current and constant prices, in millions of euro, according to the income (current prices only), output (constant prices only) and expenditure methods (current and constant prices). Value added estimates at current and constant prices are published for the five main branches of the economy. These are Agriculture, Industry, distribution/Transport/Communications, Public Administration/Defence and Other Service Industries. Expenditure on the GDP is broken down into the main categories of Final Demand, including Personal (19 product groups) and Government consumption, Investment (six product groups) and Imports and Exports. Accounts are compiled in accordance with ESA 95. The quarterly release is less detailed than the annual. The income estimate is not provided on a quarterly basis nor are the breakdowns of personal expenditure or capital formation.

Name: Italy Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1861 To Dec 1959
Quarterly From Mar 1960 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: The method used is the model-based approach as given in the program TRAMO-SEATS. Working DAy adjustment is applied to the basic monthly indicators (where available) Seasonal adjustment is applied to the working day adjusted quarterly indicators. Data are disseminated in millions of euro on GDP at current and constant 1995 prices, together with implicit deflators, compiled using the expenditure approach and the production approach. The data cover the entire economy. Data are disseminated on current and constant price GDP showing a breakdown by expenditure category as follows: (1) compensation of employees (further broken down by productive sector); (2) gross fixed capital formation (further broken down by productive sector); (3) final domestic consumption (further broken down by purpose and by type of good); and (4) labor input (in full-time equivalents). The data are disseminated in both unadjusted and seasonally-adjusted formats.

Name: Netherlands Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1807 To Dec 1976
Quarterly From Mar 1977 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Sources: In 1990 the Dutch Science Foundation granted Prof.dr J.L. van Zanden a subsidy for the research programme "Reconstructing National Accounts of the Netherlands and the analysis of the development of the Dutch Economy in the period 1800-1940". From then onwards this programme resulted in a great number of articles and dissertations which provide a deeper understanding the the dynamics of long-term economic growth. To reconstruct national income extensive data concerning income, prices, foreign trade, production, employment and capital formation were collected and processed.The calculations of output were the starting point of the project. Initially the research was focussed on the estimations of value added in agriculture, industry and services. Major research was undertaken to reconstruct the movement of output, inputs and prices in various sectors of the economy. The work on capital formation has been equal importance. Other categories of expenditure were estimated either directly from primary source material (e.g. government expenditure) or indirect by combining data on output and foreign trade (private consumer expenditure). The income side of the accounting system was the object of two separate projects, one on wages, salaries and income inequality and another on income from capital. See the research publication Dutch GNP and its components, 1800-1913, for a description of the National Account Project (in pfd, 763 KB).See http://nationalaccounts.niwi.knaw.nl/start.htmNotes: Data are disseminated in millions of Dutch guilders on GDP at current and constant 1995 prices. The GDP data cover the entire economy. The following breakdowns are disseminated: by expenditure category, by productive sectors, NACE (rev.1), and by cost components. The breakdown by major expenditure category includes the following components: consumption expenditure by households and by government, consumption expenditure, individual and collective, gross fixed capital formation by government and by corporations, changes in stocks, and exports and imports of goods and services. The breakdowns are disseminated both in current and in constant prices. QNA uses a make-use table as an instrument for the integration of short-term statistical data on output, expenditure and income.  The data are compiled in accordance with the methodology set out in ESA95. The data are disseminated in both unadjusted and seasonally adjusted formats. However, the seasonally adjusted data are available only at a high aggregated level, such as, the supply and disposition of goods and services, gross fixed capital formation, change in inventories, and, export of goods and services.

Name: Norway Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1830 To Dec 1960
Quarterly From Mar 1961 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Sources:      Grytten, O.H. (2004). "The gross domestic product for Norway 1830-2003", 241-288,      Historical Monetary Statistics for Norway 1819-2003, Norges Bank Occasional Papers no. 35, Oslo, 2004 Notes: Data are disseminated in millions of Norwegian kroner (NOK) on GDP in current prices and in a combination of annually-chained and constant prices. The annually-chained price basis is used when the final annual national accounts of the previous year are available to provide the base for prices. If the final annual national accounts of the previous year are not available, the quarterly GDP data are reported in constant prices using the year of the latest final national accounts as the base year. (For example, if the latest final annual accounts are available for 1996, the quarterly GDP data for the period up to and including Q4 1997 are reported on an annually-chained basis, and the quarterly GDP for the period from Q1 1998 onwards are reported using 1996 constant prices.) The GDP data cover the entire Norwegian economy and are compiled using both by expenditure and production methods.  Breakdowns are disseminated on final expenditure categories and gross domestic product in current and constant prices, and the percentage changes in volume and prices. Final consumption is broken down by institutional sectors: households; non-profit institutions serving households (NPISHs); and central and local government. Gross fixed capital formation is broken down by main industries: petroleum activities; ocean transport; manufacturing and mining; other goods-producing industries; dwelling services; other market services; and general government services. Exports and imports are broken down by main categories of products. Data are also disseminated showing breakdowns on productive sectors, including breakdowns for aggregate industries, both in current and constant prices and in percentage changes in volume and prices.  Data on saving and gross national income are published annually only, but are implicitly available on a quarterly basis. The quarterly data are not seasonally adjusted, but some seasonally adjusted annual series are published in Ã˜konomiske Analyser.

Name: Portugal Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1870 To Dec 1976
Quarterly From Mar 1977 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
Notes: Data from 1870 to 1970 are from Portuguese Historical Statistics, table 6.6C for 1870-1953 and table 6.6B for 1954-93 (http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_publicacoes&PUBLICACOESpub_boui=138364&PUBLICACOESmodo=2)
Data are disseminated in millions of Euro on GDP in current prices and in constant 1995 prices, compiled by the expenditure and production methods. The data cover the entire economy of Portugal. The expenditure-based data are broken down into: private final consumption, collective consumption, gross fixed capital formation, imports of goods and services, and exports of goods and services. Private consumption (in the economic territory) is divided into: agriculture and food goods, durable goods, and current private consumption. Gross Capital Formation is divided into Gross Fixed Capital Formation, Acquisitions Less Disposable of Valuables and Changes in Stocks. Gross fixed capital formation is divided into: agriculture products, machinery and other equipment, transport material, construction, and other products. Data on gross value added in constant 1995 prices is disseminated for the following activities: agriculture, hunting, forestry and fishing; electricity, gas and water; industry; trade, restaurants and hotels; transports and communications; banking, insurance and renting activities; other services. The estimates for all activities, except agriculture, and all expenditure categories, except collective consumption, are based on primary quarterly data collected during the period, and are compiled using econometric techniques. The data for agriculture and collective consumption are based on primary annual data.
The data are estimated according to the ESA (European System of Accounts) 95. The basic statistics are seasonally adjusted.

Name: Spain Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1850 To Dec 1969
Quarterly From Mar 1970 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Notes: Annual data from 1850 is from Estadisticas Historicas, Siglos XIX-XX, p. 1332.
Data are disseminated in millions of euro on the Gross Domestic Product at current and constant 1995 prices. The data cover the entire economy. The data are compiled using the expenditure method, the production method and the income method. Breakdowns are disseminated for the following demand, supply and income aggregates: (1) Demand: final national private consumption; collective consumption of general government; gross fixed capital formation, further broken down into capital goods, and construction; change in stocks; export of goods and services; imports of goods and services. (2) Supply: Gross value added at basic prices by kind of activity, broken down into: agriculture, hunting, forestry and fishing; industrial activity, except construction; construction; services, further broken down into market services and non-market services; net taxes on imports; and VAT on products. (3) Income: Compensation of employees, property income and mixed income, and net taxes on production and imports. For each of the aggregates, the following information is provided: (i) value estimates at current prices; (ii) year to year rates of growth and (iii) quarter to quarter rates of growth. Estimates at (1995) constant prices are provided for demand and supply aggregates. The Quarterly National Accounts also compiles data on employment by industry (persons, jobs and full time equivalent jobs) according to ESA-95 rules. The data are disseminated as unadjusted figures, as calendar and seasonally-adjusted figures, and as trend-cycle figures (that is, data adjusted for both seasonality and irregular components). The data are compiled in accordance with the methodology of ESA 1995.

Name: Sweden Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1620 To Dec 1979
Quarterly From Mar 1980 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
Rodney Edvinsson, Annual Estimates of Swedish GDP in 1720-1800, through 1860 and Statistics Sweden from 1861 on. See Edvinsson, Rodney. 2011. "New estimates of Swedish GDP by activity 1665-2010". Department of Economic History, Stockholm University. Stockholm Papers in Economic History No. 12.
Notes: Data are disseminated on GDP for the entire Swedish economy at
current and constant prices in millions of SEK, by production and
expenditure methods. National Accounts are presented according to
SNA93/ESA95. Time series according to SNA93/ESA95 start with 1993. The weighting in calculating GDP at constant prices are changed annually, using the price level ofthe preceding year. National Accounts
presented in constant prices, including the breakdowns described below,
are shown in reference prices for 2000. The main aggregates of GDP are seasonally adjusted. Saving and gross national income, in current prices only, are also published, as well as disposable income of households in current prices.

Name: Switzerland Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1851 To Dec 1969
Quarterly From Mar 1970 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
Notes: 1851-1913 from Historical Statistics of Switzerland Online, www.fsw.uzh.ch/histstat/main.php, table Q.1a, Q.17a and Q.17b; see Halbeisen et al. (2012), pp. 1173-1177 and 1185-1214.
Pre World War I data are from Flandreau and Zumer (2004: Table 12). Data are disseminated in Swiss francs on GDP at current and constant (1980) prices, together with implicit deflators. Data are disseminated showing a breakdown of current and constant price GDP by major expenditure categories. The data are compiled in accordance withe the methodology set out in ESA 78, with the intention of moving to ESA95 in due course. The data are not seasonally adjusted. However, data are also disseminated on GDP as growth rates, which are presented in unadjusted, seasonally-adjusted, and smoothed (trend-cycle data) formats.

Name: Great Britain Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1270 To Dec 1954
Quarterly From Mar 1955 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Data from 1268 to 1870 are from England & Great Britain, 1270-1870: Stephen Broadberry, and Bruce Campbell, Alexander Klein, Mark Overton and Bas van Leeuwen, "British Economic Growth, 1270-1870: An Output -based Approach"; http://www.lse.ac.uk/economicHistory/whosWho/profiles/sbroadberry.aspxData before 1955 is from B. R. Mitchell, International Historical Statistics: Europe 1750-2000, Fourth Edition, Stockton Press, 2003. Notes: Data are disseminated in three main formats: the "Four Week" estimate; the "Eight Week" estimate; and the "Twelve Week Estimate". The last two meet the SDDS requirements and publish current and constant price data in millions of pounds Sterling. (1) The "Four Week" estimate publishes only constant price output analysis at basic prices in index number form with a base year of 1995. Data after 1920 excludes Southern Ireland.  The categories for which data are published include: Distribution, Hotels and Catering, Total Services, and Gross Domestic Product. Movements of output components at basic prices are used as an indicator of growth at market prices at this early stage. (2) The "Eight Week" estimate publishes a fuller "output" analysis, in both current and constant 1995 prices in millions of pounds Sterling. Detailed data are published showing breakdowns by productive activity, by expenditure category and by income. (a) The breakdown by productive activity shows estimates of output for: Agriculture, Hunting Forestry and Fishing; Mining and Quarrying, including oil and gas extraction; Manufacturing; Electricity, gas and water supply; Total Index of Production; Construction; Transport and Communication; Finance and Business Services; and Government and other services, as well as the aggregates published in the Four Week estimates.  (b) The breakdown by expenditure category is published in both current and constant market prices for: Household Final Expenditure; Non-profit Institutions Serving Households (NPISH) Final Expenditure; General Government Final Consumption; Gross Fixed Capital Formation; Change in Inventories; Acquisition less Disposals of Valuables; Total Exports; and Total Imports."  (c) The "income analysis" breakdown shows the following aggregates: Compensation of Employees; Gross Operating Surplus of Corporations; and Other Income. (3) The "Twelve Week" estimates publish full quarterly national accounts, including all the breakdowns indicated above, with a further disaggregation of the Income and Expenditure components, and with current, capital and financial accounts for the private nonfinancial corporations sector, household income, expenditure and saving. Estimates for Gross Domestic Product and Gross Value Added are compiled on various bases, for example, at current market prices, at basic prices, at factor cost, at constant 1995 prices and as indices where 1995=100. The data in current and constant prices are disseminated in millions of pounds Sterling. The data are published in both seasonally adjusted and unadjusted formats and are compiled in accordance with the methodology set out in ESA95.

Name: Belgium Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1835 To Dec 1979
Quarterly From Mar 1980 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
Notes: Data from 1835 to 1914 are from Historical National Accounts (http://www.rug.nl/research/ggdc/data/historical-national-accounts)
Data from 1880 to 1913 are from Flandreau and Zumer (2004: Table 12). GDP at constant and current prices, according to ESA95, calculated initially using the production approach. In addition to this production approach, complete estimates of GDP by means of the expenditure approach are also made, including private and public consumption, total gross fixed capital formation, changes in inventories (the last two being merged under the heading "gross domestic capital formation" in Belgium's National Summary Data Page), net exports. The data cover the entire Belgian economy and are seasonally adjusted. The calculation of the quarterly figures is based on the Chow-Lin method, i.e. a method of interpolation and extrapolation of certain indicators of the annual national accounts. For the main activity branches, as defined in the annual national accounts published by the ICN (Institute of National Accounts) a quarterly split up of the value added is available. These branches are: 1. Agriculture, hunting, forestry and fishing; 2. Industry; 3. Construction; 4. Trade, transport and communication; 5. Financial, real estate, renting and business activities; 6. Public administration and education; 7. Other services. (In Belgium's National Summary Data Page, item 4 to 7 are summarized under a global heading "services"). 8. Other components (Taxes less subsidies on products and Financial Intermidiation Services indirectly measured). The base year of the quarterly GDP figures is 2000. The data are published in billions of Belgian francs, and in percent changes (on an annual basis, compared to the last quarter, and compared to the same quarter of the last year). Data prior to 1948 are Net National Product.

Name: Czech Republic Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1985 To Dec 1990
Quarterly From Mar 1991 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data on gross domestic product (GDP) are disseminated at current prices, previous year's average prices, and 1995 constant prices, all as absolute values (CZK million) and as the growth rate from year to year. The data cover the entire economy of the Czech Republic. As to constant prices, they were 1995 constant prices up to March 2004 (the 4th quarter 2003 GDP estimate). In June 2004 (the 1st quarter 2004 GDP estimate) the data at previous year average prices and 2000 constant prices were published. Since September 2004 (the 2nd quarter 2004 GDP estimate) the data at previous year average prices and at the prices of 1995 obtained by chain-linking are published. The annual overlap technique is used for chain-linking.   The data are compiled in accordance with the methodology set out in ESA 1995. Data on GDP are disseminated broken down by expenditure categories as follows: household expenditures; non-profit institution expenditures; government institutions expenditures (individual and collective); gross fixed capital formation; changes in stocks; exports of goods; exports of services; imports of goods; and imports of services. Data on gross value added broken down by NACE categories and data on the encouraged components of saving and gross national income are also published. The data since 1994 have been published both as non-adjusted and seasonally adjusted ones. In addition, the indices derived from seasonally adjusted time series of the GDP expenditure categories are published. The TRAMO/SEATS method (Demetra 2.0) is used for the seasonal adjustments. The seasonally adjusted time series were not published in June 2004. The reason was that the historical revision of the quarterly NA was not completed in June. The seasonally adjusted data on GDP and GDP expenditures (only from the year 1995) were released on September 14, 2004. The completed seasonally adjusted data on GDP resources and expenditures were again released on December 10, 2004 (comprising time-series from the year 1995). For the first time, a correction for a number of working days in individual periods was performed on selected time series for which the influence of different numbers of working days is statistically significant.

Name: Denmark Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1818 To Dec 1976
Quarterly From Mar 1977 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Annual data are from Abildgren (2008: 40-41) and from Historical National Accounts (http://www.rug.nl/research/ggdc/data/historical-national-accounts). GDP at current and constant prices, together with implicit deflators, by production and expenditure methods, all at annual rates. Breakdowns are as specified in the European System of Accounts, (ESA 1995). Savings and Gross National income are also published.  The data cover the entire economy and both seasonally adjusted and non-seasonally adjusted figures are published.

Name: Austria Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1870 To Dec 1956
Quarterly From Mar 1957 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Pre-World War I data are from Jobst and Scheiber (2014: series AH6A_A). Data are for GNP through 1963 and GDP from 1964 on. Data are disseminated in thousands of Euro on GDP at current and chained 2000 Euro covering the total economy, together with implicit deflators, by kind of activity, expenditure and income. Breakdowns are as specified in European System of National Accounts 1995 (ESA 95). Data are published at current and chained 2000 Euro. With TRAMO-SEATS seasonally and working day adjusted series are available as well. The quarterly results are summing up to the annual results. Figures are based on primary data of the same reference period (e.g. production index, construction reporting, foreign trade statistics, monthly sales, bank records and other quarterly and monthly statistics) and are compiled using econometric techniques.

Name: Finland Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1860 To Dec 1969
Quarterly From Mar 1970 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated in millions of Euro on Gross Domestic Product at current prices and constant 2000 prices. The data cover the entire economy. The data are compiled by the expenditure approach at both current and constant 2000 prices. The data are compiled by the production approach at both current and constant 2000 prices. A breakdown of current and constant price GDP by major expenditure category is disseminated as follows: exports and imports of goods and services; government consumption; private consumption by durability; government and private gross fixed capital formation by type of investment; changes in inventories, statistical discrepancy. A breakdown of constant price GDP by kind of activity is disseminated for 21 branches. Data on National income are disseminated at current prices and constant 2000 prices. The data series begins with 1975. The data on quarterly national accounts are compiled according to the European System of Accounts (ESA 95). Original and seasonally adjusted and trend series are available.

Name: Japan Nominal GDP
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1885 To Dec 1979
Quarterly From Mar 1980 To Sep 2020
Metadata: Source: K. Ohkawa et al., Long Term economic Statistics of Japan Since 1868, v. 14 (Tokyo, 1979). Data are for GNP to 1930 and GDP thereafter.  Notes: Data are disseminated in thousand millions of Yen on nominal and real GDP, together with the implicit deflators. The data are compiled using the GDP by expenditure for flow accounts and the private capital assets for stock accounts, both of which cover the entire Japanese economy. The current and constant price data are broken down by major expenditure category as follows: private consumption (which is further broken down to household consumption and household consumption excluding imputed rents); residential private investment; nonresidential private investment; increase in private inventory; government consumption; public investment; increase in public inventory; exports of goods and services; and imports of goods and services. Regarding the stock accounts, the constant price data are broken down by major private industry in the format of progress type and attachment type both for the assets and the new investments. In addition, Gross Domestic Income, Gross National Income and Compensation of Employees are also available at both current and constant prices. Data are published in both original and seasonally-adjusted formats using X-12-ARIMA.
